var QUIZ_QUESTIONS=[{id:1,tier:"red",q:"Linguistic diversity is not spread evenly across the globe. According to the lectures, areas with a high concentration of different human languages also tend to have extremely high levels of:",opts:["Formal education","Geographic isolation","Plant biodiversity","Trade routes"],ans:2,reason:"Linguistic diversity refers to how many different languages exist in a specific area. When mapping out where the world's 7,000 languages are spoken, researchers found a direct, geographical correlation: regions with high biological plant diversity (like tropical rainforests) also harbor the highest concentrations of distinct human languages."},{id:2,tier:"red",q:"Vervet monkeys have specific alarm calls for specific predators (like eagles vs. snakes). However, human language is entirely unique because it possesses a property called:",opts:["Abstract referentiality","Compositionality","Displaced referentiality","Instinctive meaning"],ans:0,reason:"\"Referentiality\" is the ability to use a sound to refer to a specific thing in the real world. While animals like monkeys have basic referentiality (they can call out a warning for a snake that is right in front of them), human language is unique because it possesses abstract referentiality. This means humans can use language to refer to abstract concepts, invisible ideas, or things that do not physically exist."},{id:3,tier:"red",q:"Researchers taught chimpanzees to use American Sign Language (ASL). What specific communicative intention made up the vast majority of the apes' signing?",opts:["Describing past events","Requesting things","Warning of danger","Asking questions"],ans:1,reason:"When researchers successfully taught apes manual signs, they found that the apes did not use language the way humans do. Instead of sharing observations or discussing ideas, a tiny handful of signs accounted for almost all of their communication, and their primary intention was almost exclusively making requests (e.g., asking for food, tickles, or toys)."},{id:4,tier:"red",q:"When humans talk about the location of objects in space, we use \"Frames of Reference.\" At which spatial scale do languages exhibit the most variation across different cultures?",opts:["The geographic scale","The table-top scale","The allocentric scale","The cross-continental scale"],ans:1,reason:"A \"Frame of Reference\" is the coordinate system a language uses to describe where things are. While almost all cultures use an absolute, world-based system (like North/South) for massive geographic scales, cultures vary drastically in the systems they use for small, immediate spaces directly in front of them, which researchers call the \"table-top scale\"."},{id:5,tier:"red",q:"In \"rotation experiments,\" subjects view objects on a table, rotate 180 degrees, and recreate the arrangement on a new table. How did Dutch speakers and Tzeltal speakers respond?",opts:["Both groups used an absolute (geocentric) Frame of Reference.","Dutch speakers recreated it egocentrically; Tzeltal speakers recreated it geocentrically.","Dutch speakers recreated it geocentrically; Tzeltal speakers recreated it egocentrically.","Both groups struggled to remember the arrangement."],ans:1,reason:"\"Egocentric\" means relating space to your own body (e.g., \"to my left\"), while \"Geocentric\" means relating space to the world (e.g., \"to the North\"). In this memory task, Dutch speakers recreated the arrangement relative to their own bodies, while Tzeltal speakers recreated it relative to compass directions. This proves that the language you speak dictates how your brain stores non-linguistic spatial memories."},{id:6,tier:"red",q:"\"Codability\" refers to how easy it is to put a sensory experience into words. According to the traditional Aristotelian hierarchy, which sense is considered the least codable?",opts:["Vision","Hearing","Taste","Smell"],ans:3,reason:"Codability is a measure of how easily a culture can describe something. The traditional Western (Aristotelian) hierarchy dictates that Vision is the easiest to describe, followed by Hearing, Touch, Taste, and finally Smell, making odor historically viewed as the most un-codable human sense."},{id:7,tier:"red",q:"The Jahai and Semaq Beri peoples easily name odors using abstract \"basic smell words.\" What lifestyle factor do they share that heavily correlates with this ability?",opts:["They are horticulturalists (farmers).","They have formal education systems.","They are hunter-gatherer groups.","They speak polysynthetic languages."],ans:2,reason:"While Western cultures struggle to name smells (often relying on comparisons like \"it smells like a lemon\"), the Jahai and Semaq Beri use dedicated \"basic smell words\". This is because both are hunter-gatherer societies\u2014a subsistence mode that requires a heightened reliance on identifying wild odors, which directly shapes their language to make smells highly codable."},{id:8,tier:"red",q:"Why did researchers specifically compare the smell codability of the Semalai and the Semaq Beri groups?",opts:["They speak the exact same language but live on different continents.","They live in the exact same environment, allowing researchers to isolate lifestyle (hunter-gatherer vs. farmer) as the true cause.","One group is completely deaf.","They represent the two extremes of phoneme inventories."],ans:1,reason:"If researchers compared a forest tribe to a city population, critics could argue the forest tribe is better at naming smells simply because forests have more odors. By comparing the Semalai (farmers) and the Semaq Beri (hunter-gatherers) who live in the exact same tropical rainforest, researchers proved that ecology doesn't drive codability; the culture's subsistence mode does."},{id:9,tier:"red",q:"Languages like Cayuga and Turkish string massive amounts of basic meanings (morphemes) together into a single, highly complex word. These languages are classified as:",opts:["Analytic","Polysynthetic","Allocentric","Egocentric"],ans:1,reason:"Languages package meaning differently. \"Analytic\" languages (like English) use separate, stand-alone words to build a sentence. \"Polysynthetic\" languages fuse many smaller units of meaning together, essentially packing an entire sentence's worth of information into one massive, dense word."},{id:10,tier:"orange",q:"At what point did human linguistic diversity reach its absolute peak, and roughly how many languages existed?",opts:["100,000 years ago; 1 to 50 languages","12,000 BC; roughly 100,000 languages","3300 BC; roughly 15,000 languages","1500 AD; roughly 7,000 languages"],ans:1,reason:"Diversity peaked around 12,000 BC because early hunter-gatherer bands constantly splintered and spread across the globe in search of resources, allowing their languages to evolve independently."},{id:11,tier:"orange",q:"What primary historical force caused the rapid decline in human linguistic diversity from its peak down to the ~7,000 languages we have today?",opts:["A sudden global drop in plant biodiversity.","\"Big\" languages displacing \"little\" ones, accelerated by text-based technologies.","The transition from an edge-to-edge bite to an overbite.","The invention of agriculture."],ans:1,reason:"We are currently experiencing a massive language extinction. This is caused by large, dominant languages swallowing up smaller ones\u2014a process heavily catalyzed by the invention of writing, printing, the internet, and other text-based technologies that allow big languages to scale."},{id:12,tier:"orange",q:"The invention of writing in Mesopotamia (~3300 BC) was considered a \"seismic event.\" What was its original, primary purpose?",opts:["Recording historical narratives","Translating spoken language into a visual medium","Accounting, utilizing 3D clay tokens for goods","Standardizing phonetic alphabets"],ans:2,reason:"Humans did not invent writing with the grand goal of recording spoken language. We stumbled into it purely for accounting purposes, evolving the system from physical 3D clay tokens used to track goods into 2D marks on clay tablets."},{id:13,tier:"orange",q:"A honeybee's waggle dance communicates the distance and heading of a location. This is a perfect example of which linguistic property?",opts:["Basic referentiality","Compositionality","Displaced referentiality","Abstract referentiality"],ans:2,reason:"\"Displaced\" referentiality is the ability to communicate about something that is not physically present in the current time or space. Because the bee is talking about a food source that is far away and out of sight, it demonstrates displacement."},{id:14,tier:"orange",q:"When learning a second language, achieving native-like pronunciation is difficult due to the \"fossilization\" of mouth muscles. Therefore, the actual goal of second-language pronunciation should be:",opts:["Complete deviation","Comprehensibility (making clear distinctions for phonemes that change meaning)","Mastering all 100+ possible human phonemes","Perfecting the McGurk effect"],ans:1,reason:"\"Fossilization\" occurs when our brain and mouth muscles become rigidly adapted to the sounds of our mother tongue. Having an accent is normal; instead of trying to perfectly mimic native sounds, language learners should focus on comprehensibility\u2014ensuring they clearly distinguish sounds that actually alter a word's meaning (like the difference between /r/ and /l/)."},{id:15,tier:"orange",q:"The English plural ending sounds like /s/ in cats, /z/ in cabs, and /ez/ in buses. What is the linguistic term for these phonetic variations of a single meaning?",opts:["Ideophones","Allomorphs","Phonaesthemes","Free morphemes"],ans:1,reason:"A \"morpheme\" is the smallest unit of meaning. An \"allomorph\" is a variation of that morpheme that changes its sound based on the phonetic environment of the word it is attached to, without changing its underlying meaning."},{id:16,tier:"orange",q:"In Jean Berko Gleason's \"Wug Test,\" a child is shown a fictional creature called a Wug, and is asked to name two of them. What did this experiment definitively prove?",opts:["Children implicitly learn and apply grammatical rules to words they have never heard before.","Children rely entirely on source descriptions to learn new words.","Children naturally utilize an egocentric Frame of Reference.","Children learn language primarily through the McGurk effect."],ans:0,reason:"Because \"Wug\" is a completely made-up nonsense word, a child could not have simply memorized its plural form beforehand. When they correctly say \"Wugs\", it proves their brain has internalized the invisible rule for pluralization and can apply it dynamically to new situations."},{id:17,tier:"orange",q:"What does the \"McGurk Effect\" prove about human speech perception?",opts:["Humans cannot hear labiodental sounds without an overbite.","Context\u2014specifically visual context\u2014shapes how our brains perceive speech sounds.","Chimpanzees cannot combine morphemes.","Spatial memory dictates vocabulary."],ans:1,reason:"Speech perception is multimodal, meaning our brains use multiple senses at once. The McGurk effect shows that if you look at a video of a person mouthing the sound \"fa\" while an audio track plays the sound \"ba\", your brain will fuse the visual and auditory inputs, causing you to actually hear \"fa\"."},{id:18,tier:"orange",q:"Words like the, and, in are structural and rarely get new additions. Words like cat, run, binge-watch carry core meaning and get new additions constantly. What are these two classes of words called?",opts:["Structural words are an open class; meaning words are a closed class.","Both are considered open classes.","Function words are a closed class; content words are an open class.","Function words are polysynthetic; content words are analytic."],ans:2,reason:"\"Function words\" build the grammar of a sentence and are a \"closed class\" (there are only about 300 in English, and society rarely invents new ones). \"Content words\" carry the actual meaning and are an \"open class\" (there are hundreds of thousands, and society constantly invents new ones like binge-watch or ghosting)."},{id:19,tier:"orange",q:"In the \"ZIV/KERN\" experiment, 4-year-old English-speaking children were taught nonsense words for their arms. When spun around 180 degrees, 73% of the children assumed the words mapped to:",opts:["Their own bodies (Egocentric bias)","The sides of the room (Allocentric/Geocentric bias)","The intrinsic sides of the researcher","The tabletop scale"],ans:1,reason:"Even though Western adults are heavily egocentric (body-focused), these young children assumed the new words referred to absolute directions in the room (e.g., \"the wall over there\"). This suggests humans may actually start with a natural, geocentric bias before our specific culture trains us to be egocentric."},{id:20,tier:"orange",q:"In the Haun et al. (2011) spatial experiment, children were explicitly instructed to use a different Frame of Reference strategy than they normally use. What did their success prove?",opts:["Geocentric frames of reference are impossible to use indoors.","Language strictly dictates what humans can and cannot perceive.","Cross-cultural variations in spatial reasoning are a matter of cultural preference, not a lack of cognitive competence.","Children have a natural egocentric bias."],ans:2,reason:"Because the children could successfully use the opposite spatial strategy when forced to, it proved their brains had the capacity (competence) to do it. They simply don't normally do it because their culture trained them to prefer one strategy over the other."},{id:21,tier:"yellow",q:"English words that share similar sound clusters and related meanings, such as gleam, glitz, glamor, glow, and glitter, demonstrate which linguistic phenomenon?",opts:["Allomorphs","Phonaesthemes","Open class words","Bound morphemes"],ans:1,reason:"Phonaesthemes are specific clusters of sounds (like the \"gl-\" sound) that have become consistently associated with a specific semantic meaning (like \"light\" or \"shining\") across multiple words in a language vocabulary."},{id:22,tier:"yellow",q:"\"The Arbitrariness of the Sign\" states that words do not inherently sound like their meaning. However, Japanese words like pikapika (bright) and nurunuru (slimy) are prime examples of the exception to this rule, known as:",opts:["Phonaesthemes","Polysynthetic grammar","Ideophones","Compound words"],ans:2,reason:"While the word \"dog\" has nothing physically \"dog-like\" about its sound (arbitrary), \"ideophones\" are rare words specifically engineered so that their phonetic sounds evoke their actual physical meaning (non-arbitrary)."},{id:23,tier:"yellow",q:"The lecture notes that a pig says \"Oink\" in English, \"Buu\" in Japanese, and \"N\u00f6ff\" in Swedish. This example is specifically used to demonstrate:",opts:["Phonaesthemes","The Arbitrariness of the Sign","Fossilization","The McGurk Effect"],ans:1,reason:"This proves that even when humans attempt to mimic the exact same physical animal noise, the resulting words are still completely arbitrary and defined by the cultural rules of the language."},{id:24,tier:"yellow",q:"Which biological change occurred roughly 3,600 years ago, making it significantly easier for humans to produce labiodental sounds (like /f/ and /v/)?",opts:["The dropping of the larynx","The transition from an edge-to-edge bite to an overbite","The recycling of the \"Visual Word Form Area\"","The fossilization of the vocal cords"],ans:1,reason:"The shift to agriculture and eating softer foods caused human jaw structures to slowly change from an edge-to-edge bite to an overbite. This physical change allowed the top teeth to easily rest on the bottom lip, enabling the massive global spread of labiodental sounds like /f/ and /v/."},{id:25,tier:"yellow",q:"Researchers have attempted to teach human language to various apes. Which of the following apes successfully learned to use a \"lexigram board\" without explicit instruction?",opts:["Nim Chimpsky","Washoe","Viki","Kanzi"],ans:3,reason:"While chimpanzees like Nim and Washoe were explicitly, painstakingly taught manual ASL signs, Kanzi (a bonobo) reportedly absorbed and mastered over 200 lexigrams (symbols on a board) spontaneously without direct, explicit instruction."},{id:26,tier:"yellow",q:"Which animal demonstrates \"basic compositionality\" by combining distinct sounds (like hok and oo) to create new meanings?",opts:["Vervet monkeys","Dolphins","Campbell's monkeys","Honeybees"],ans:2,reason:"\"Compositionality\" is the ability to build complex meanings out of smaller parts. Campbell's monkeys demonstrate a basic version of this by taking a root alarm call (hok for eagle) and adding an affix (oo) to change the meaning to a general arboreal disturbance."},{id:27,tier:"yellow",q:"In the \"Animals in a Row\" experiment, participants were tested on a spatial task with the room's blinds down, and then with the blinds up. What was the main finding?",opts:["Access to implicit landmarks matters for spatial reasoning.","Children cannot use geocentric frames of reference indoors.","Animals are inherently remembered intrinsically.","Vision is the most codable sense."],ans:0,reason:"When the blinds were raised (allowing participants to see the outside world and its geographic features), their spatial problem-solving strategies shifted, proving that visual access to environmental landmarks strongly influences how we map space in our heads."},{id:28,tier:"yellow",q:"Literacy is very \"new on the scene\" from an evolutionary standpoint. Because of this, how do our brains adapt to the invention of reading?",opts:["Our brains grow an entirely new lobe dedicated to reading.","We use the exact same brain region used for auditory processing.","A patch of the visual cortex, originally evolved to recognize object contours in nature, is rapidly recycled for reading.","The brain relies entirely on the prefrontal cortex to decode symbols."],ans:2,reason:"Because writing was invented so recently, humans did not have time to evolve a specific \"reading center\" in the brain. Instead, our brains \"recycle\" existing visual architecture to decode text, which researchers now call the \"visual word form area\"."},{id:29,tier:"yellow",q:"To prove how profoundly spatial language impacts our behavior, the lecture contrasts how children from different cultures learn to dance. How do Namibian (Hai||om) children naturally learn to dance compared to German children?",opts:["Both groups learn using egocentric directions.","Namibian children dance using absolute/geocentric directions, while German children dance using egocentric directions.","Namibian children dance using intrinsic directions.","Both groups learn using geocentric directions."],ans:1,reason:"Because the Hai||om language relies on a geocentric frame of reference, even their physical, non-linguistic activities like dancing are mapped out relative to the compass directions of the world, rather than relative to the left/right sides of their own bodies."},{id:30,tier:"yellow",q:"Which of the following is TRUE regarding sign languages across the globe?",opts:["They are simply manual translations of the local spoken language.","They tend to spring up in communities with high rates of hereditary deafness and are generally much younger than spoken languages.","There are over 7,000 distinct sign languages currently in use.","They are the oldest form of human communication."],ans:1,reason:"There are roughly 200 sign languages globally. They are distinct, natural languages with their own grammar; they are not mere translations of spoken languages, and they often spring up organically in deaf communities."},{id:31,tier:"green",q:"In Lecture 1, the professor shows a map illustrating the massive historical dispersal of the Austronesian language family. According to the map, where did these peoples and languages originate before spreading to Madagascar and Hawaii?",opts:["Mesopotamia","Taiwan","Papua New Guinea","South Africa"],ans:1,reason:"The map explicitly traces the origin point of the Austronesian language dispersal starting from Taiwan around 3000 BC and spreading outward across the oceans."},{id:32,tier:"green",q:"A specific graphic demonstrates how heavily concentrated human language has become. Out of the ~7,000 languages in the world today, how many are spoken by over half of the global population (4.1 billion people)?",opts:["Just 1 language (English)","23 languages","150 languages","850 languages"],ans:1,reason:"While there are thousands of languages, a tiny fraction\u2014just 23 \"big\" languages (like Chinese, Spanish, English, Hindi)\u2014account for the native tongues of over half the planet, illustrating massive linguistic inequality."},{id:33,tier:"green",q:"In Sean's mini-lecture on accents, he notes that accents are not just about producing individual phonemes (like /r/ vs /l/). What other linguistic feature did he explicitly mention impacts meaning in different accents?",opts:["Ideophones","Sentence stress","Geocentric frames","Abstract referentiality"],ans:1,reason:"Accents also involve what happens when sounds are produced together in a flow, and how the rhythm or sentence stress (prosody) changes meaning across different speakers."},{id:34,tier:"green",q:"To highlight differences in geographic concentration, the professor contrasted the United States with Papua New Guinea. What was the key takeaway?",opts:["The US has over 850 indigenous languages, while Papua New Guinea has only 150.","The US has roughly 150 indigenous languages, whereas Papua New Guinea (despite being about the size of California) has roughly 850.","Both countries have roughly 7,000 languages.","Papua New Guinea relies primarily on a whistled speech surrogate."],ans:1,reason:"This specific contrast is used to highlight how incredibly dense linguistic diversity can be in certain biodiversity hotspots (like PNG) compared to massive, industrialized landmasses like the US."},{id:35,tier:"green",q:"To demonstrate how some languages pack an incredible amount of meaning into a single word, the lecture uses an example from Cayuga (a Native American language). Which English sentence translates to just a single word in Cayuga?",opts:["\"I will plant potatoes for them again\"","\"Kill two birds with one stone\"","\"20 days from today\"","\"A generalized arboreal disturbance\""],ans:0,reason:"This is the prime slide example of how heavily polysynthetic languages package complex sentences into single units."},{id:36,tier:"green",q:"Languages also differ in how they package complex time concepts. According to the slides, which language has a single, specific word that translates to \"20 days from today\"?",opts:["Rotokas","Yeli Dnye (PNG)","Taa","Tzeltal"],ans:1,reason:"While English uses the word \"tomorrow\" for a relatively simple concept, Yeli Dnye has invented a specific single word for a highly complex time concept."},{id:37,tier:"green",q:"Conversely, some languages do not have words for concepts that English speakers would consider basic. What specific example did the lecture provide for this?",opts:["Many Australian Aboriginal languages have no word for 'seven'.","The Jahai have no basic smell words.","The Semalai have no words for colors.","Lao does not have nouns."],ans:0,reason:"This demonstrates that what one culture considers a \"basic\" concept requiring a dedicated word (like higher numbers) is entirely relative to their cultural needs."},{id:38,tier:"green",q:"To prove that languages are constantly adding new \"open class\" words, the professor showed a list of the American Dialect Society's \"Words of the Year.\" Which of the following words were explicitly listed as examples?",opts:["Wug, KERN, and ZIV","Binge-watch, salty, and ghost","Pikapika, nurunuru, and wakuwaku","Oink, buu, and n\u00f6ff"],ans:1,reason:"These were specifically highlighted as words added to the English lexicon recently, proving that \"content words\" belong to an open, endlessly growing and evolving class."},{id:39,tier:"green",q:"The lecture discusses how idioms often have remarkably similar structures across languages due to historical borrowing. According to the slides, what is the German/Dutch equivalent of \"kill two birds with one stone\"?",opts:["\"Hit two flies with one blow\"","\"Catch two pigeons with one fava bean\"","\"Kill two hares with one bullet\"","\"Catch two fish with one hook\""],ans:0,reason:"A map in the lecture shows regional variations: English uses \"birds/stone,\" Spanish/Portuguese use \"hares/bullet,\" and German/Dutch use \"flies/blow\"."},{id:40,tier:"green",q:"To further hammer home the \"Arbitrariness of the Sign,\" the professor shows the cross-cultural words for a frog's croak. What is the Japanese word for a frog's sound?",opts:["Kwaak","Ribbit","KeroKero","Vrak"],ans:2,reason:"The graphic shows that an English frog says \"Ribbit,\" a German frog says \"Kwaak,\" and a Japanese frog says \"KeroKero,\" reinforcing that even mimicry is defined by cultural rules."},{id:41,tier:"green",q:"While writing was invented around 3300 BC, the global literacy rate remained incredibly low for most of human history. According to the \"Literate vs. Illiterate World Population\" chart, roughly when did the global literate population finally surpass the illiterate population?",opts:["Around 1500 AD","Around 1800 AD","Sometime after 1950 AD","It hasn't; the majority of the world is still illiterate"],ans:2,reason:"The chart explicitly shows that global literacy is incredibly \"new on the scene,\" only crossing the 50% threshold to overtake the illiterate population in the mid-to-late 20th century."},{id:42,tier:"green",q:"Researchers tried various methods to teach apes language. Which of the following chimpanzees was raised exactly like a human child in a human home, but was considered a failure because she could only physically produce 4 words?",opts:["Nim Chimpsky","Viki","Washoe","Koko"],ans:1,reason:"Viki's failure proved that apes simply do not have the vocal tract anatomy to physically produce human speech, which is why subsequent researchers pivoted entirely to teaching them manual ASL signs."},{id:43,tier:"green",q:"Languages vary in which word classes they use. Which of the following examples was given in the lectures to show that not all languages have the same grammatical building blocks as English?",opts:["English has no ideophones.","Lao does not have adjectives.","Cayuga does not have nouns.","Turkish does not have morphemes."],ans:1,reason:"While English speakers assume adjectives are a universal building block of language, the lectures highlight that Lao is a language that operates entirely without them."}];

