var KEY_TERMS={
1:[{term:"Linguistic diversity",def:"The number of different languages spoken in a specific geographic area."},{term:"Plant biodiversity correlation",def:"From lectures: regions with high biological plant diversity (tropical rainforests) also have the highest concentrations of distinct human languages. This is a geographical correlation, not causation."}],
2:[{term:"Referentiality",def:"The ability to use a sound to refer to a specific thing in the real world."},{term:"Abstract referentiality",def:"Unique to humans: the ability to refer to abstract concepts, invisible ideas, or things that do not physically exist."},{term:"Basic referentiality",def:"Animals like vervet monkeys can call out warnings for things present in front of them."}],
3:[{term:"Ape language experiments",def:"Researchers taught apes (Washoe, Nim, Kanzi) manual signs or lexigrams."},{term:"Key finding",def:"Apes' signing was almost exclusively making requests (food, tickles, toys) — not sharing observations or discussing ideas."}],
4:[{term:"Frame of Reference (FoR)",def:"The coordinate system a language uses to describe spatial locations."},{term:"Egocentric FoR",def:"Relating space to your own body (e.g., 'to my left')."},{term:"Geocentric/Absolute FoR",def:"Relating space to the world (e.g., 'to the North')."},{term:"Table-top scale",def:"The small, immediate space directly in front of you — where cultures vary the MOST in their FoR."}],
5:[{term:"Rotation experiments",def:"Subjects view objects on a table, rotate 180 degrees, recreate arrangement on a new table."},{term:"Dutch speakers",def:"Recreated arrangement egocentrically (relative to their own bodies)."},{term:"Tzeltal speakers",def:"Recreated arrangement geocentrically (relative to compass directions)."}],
6:[{term:"Codability",def:"How easy it is to put a sensory experience into words."},{term:"Aristotelian hierarchy",def:"Vision (most codable) > Hearing > Touch > Taste > Smell (least codable)."}],
7:[{term:"Jahai & Semaq Beri",def:"Hunter-gatherer groups that have dedicated 'basic smell words' — abstract terms for odors."},{term:"Subsistence mode",def:"Hunter-gatherer lifestyle requires heightened reliance on identifying wild odors, shaping language to make smells highly codable."}],
8:[{term:"Semalai",def:"Farmers living in the same tropical rainforest as the Semaq Beri."},{term:"Semaq Beri",def:"Hunter-gatherers in the same environment as the Semalai."},{term:"Key insight",def:"Same environment, different lifestyles — proves ecology doesn't drive codability; the culture's subsistence mode does."}],
9:[{term:"Analytic languages",def:"Languages (like English) that use separate, stand-alone words to build sentences."},{term:"Polysynthetic languages",def:"Languages (like Cayuga, Turkish) that fuse many morphemes into one massive, dense word — packing a whole sentence into one word."},{term:"Morpheme",def:"The smallest unit of meaning in a language."}],
10:[{term:"Peak linguistic diversity",def:"~12,000 BC with roughly 100,000 languages."},{term:"Why the peak",def:"Hunter-gatherer bands constantly splintered and spread, allowing languages to evolve independently."}],
11:[{term:"Language extinction",def:"Big languages displacing little ones — accelerated by writing, printing, internet."},{term:"Text-based technologies",def:"Allow dominant languages to scale, swallowing smaller languages."}],
12:[{term:"Invention of writing",def:"~3300 BC in Mesopotamia."},{term:"Original purpose",def:"Accounting — evolved from physical 3D clay tokens for tracking goods into 2D marks on clay tablets. NOT for recording speech."}],
13:[{term:"Displaced referentiality",def:"Communicating about something not physically present in the current time or space."},{term:"Honeybee waggle dance",def:"Classic example: bee communicates about a food source that is far away and out of sight."}],
14:[{term:"Fossilization",def:"Brain and mouth muscles become rigidly adapted to sounds of your mother tongue."},{term:"Comprehensibility",def:"The goal of L2 pronunciation: clearly distinguish sounds that change a word's meaning (like /r/ vs /l/)."}],
15:[{term:"Morpheme",def:"The smallest unit of meaning."},{term:"Allomorph",def:"A variation of a morpheme that changes its sound based on phonetic environment without changing meaning. Example: English plural /s/, /z/, /ez/."}],
16:[{term:"Wug Test (Berko, 1958)",def:"Child shown fictional creature 'Wug', asked to name two. Saying 'Wugs' proves children internalize grammatical rules and apply them to never-heard words."}],
17:[{term:"McGurk Effect",def:"Visual context shapes speech perception. Seeing mouth say 'fa' while hearing 'ba' makes you hear 'fa'. Proves speech perception is multimodal."}],
18:[{term:"Function words (closed class)",def:"Structural words (the, and, in) — ~300 in English, rarely get new additions."},{term:"Content words (open class)",def:"Meaning words (cat, run, binge-watch) — hundreds of thousands, constantly growing."}],
19:[{term:"ZIV/KERN experiment",def:"4-year-olds taught nonsense words for arms, spun 180 degrees."},{term:"Finding",def:"73% assumed words mapped to sides of the room (geocentric bias), not their bodies — suggesting natural geocentric starting point before cultural training."}],
20:[{term:"Haun et al. (2011)",def:"Children instructed to use opposite FoR strategy."},{term:"Finding",def:"Success proved cross-cultural variations are cultural preference, not lack of cognitive competence."}],
21:[{term:"Phonaesthemes",def:"Sound clusters (like 'gl-') consistently associated with a meaning ('light/shining') across multiple words: gleam, glitz, glamor, glow, glitter."}],
22:[{term:"Arbitrariness of the Sign",def:"Words do not inherently sound like their meaning."},{term:"Ideophones",def:"Exception: rare words whose sounds evoke their physical meaning. Japanese: pikapika (bright), nurunuru (slimy)."}],
23:[{term:"Arbitrariness of the Sign",def:"Even animal sound mimicry varies by culture: pig says 'Oink' (English), 'Buu' (Japanese), 'Noff' (Swedish)."}],
24:[{term:"Labiodental sounds",def:"Sounds like /f/ and /v/ requiring top teeth on bottom lip."},{term:"Overbite transition",def:"~3,600 years ago, shift to agriculture/softer foods changed jaw from edge-to-edge bite to overbite, enabling labiodental sounds."}],
25:[{term:"Kanzi",def:"Bonobo who learned 200+ lexigrams spontaneously without explicit instruction."},{term:"Contrast",def:"Nim Chimpsky and Washoe were explicitly, painstakingly taught ASL signs."}],
26:[{term:"Compositionality",def:"Building complex meanings from smaller parts."},{term:"Campbell's monkeys",def:"Combine root alarm call 'hok' (eagle) with affix 'oo' to create new meaning (general arboreal disturbance)."}],
27:[{term:"Animals in a Row experiment",def:"Blinds down vs. up."},{term:"Finding",def:"With blinds up (seeing landmarks), spatial strategies shifted — proving visual access to landmarks influences spatial reasoning."}],
28:[{term:"Visual Word Form Area",def:"Patch of visual cortex originally for recognizing object contours in nature, recycled for reading."},{term:"Key point",def:"Writing too recent for evolution — brain recycles existing visual architecture."}],
29:[{term:"Hai||om children (Namibia)",def:"Dance using absolute/geocentric directions (compass-based)."},{term:"German children",def:"Dance using egocentric directions (left/right body-based)."}],
30:[{term:"Sign languages",def:"~200 globally. Distinct natural languages with own grammar, NOT translations of spoken languages. Often spring up in deaf communities. Generally younger than spoken languages."}],
31:[{term:"Austronesian dispersal",def:"Origin: Taiwan (~3000 BC), spread to Madagascar and Hawaii."}],
32:[{term:"Linguistic concentration",def:"23 'big' languages spoken by 4.1 billion people (over half the world)."}],
33:[{term:"Sentence stress / prosody",def:"How rhythm and emphasis change meaning across accents — not just individual phonemes."}],
34:[{term:"US vs Papua New Guinea",def:"US: ~150 indigenous languages across massive landmass. PNG: ~850 languages in an area the size of California."}],
35:[{term:"Cayuga polysynthesis",def:"'I will plant potatoes for them again' = one single word in Cayuga."}],
36:[{term:"Yeli Dnye (PNG)",def:"Has a single word meaning '20 days from today.'"}],
37:[{term:"Lexical gaps",def:"Many Australian Aboriginal languages have no word for 'seven' — what's 'basic' depends on cultural needs."}],
38:[{term:"Open class / Content words",def:"Constantly growing: binge-watch, salty, ghost were American Dialect Society 'Words of the Year.'"}],
39:[{term:"Cross-linguistic idioms",def:"English: 'kill two birds with one stone.' German/Dutch: 'hit two flies with one blow.' Spanish/Portuguese: 'kill two hares with one bullet.'"}],
40:[{term:"Frog sounds across cultures",def:"English: Ribbit. German: Kwaak. Japanese: KeroKero. Proves arbitrariness even in mimicry."}],
41:[{term:"Global literacy timeline",def:"Writing invented ~3300 BC. Literate population didn't surpass illiterate until after 1950 AD."}],
42:[{term:"Viki",def:"Chimpanzee raised as human child. Could only produce 4 words physically. Proved apes lack vocal tract for speech — led to pivot to ASL."}],
43:[{term:"Lao",def:"A language that operates entirely without adjectives — proves word classes aren't universal."}]
};

OVERVIEW_HTML = '<div class="card" style="margin-top:8px">' +
  '<h2 style="color:#fff;font-size:22px;margin-bottom:20px;font-weight:700">Lecture 1: Language in Broad Perspective</h2>' +
  '<p style="color:#888;font-size:14px;margin-bottom:28px">Course intro — the big picture of human language, its diversity, its history, and its future.</p>' +

  '<div style="margin-bottom:28px">' +
    '<h3 style="color:#fff;font-size:16px;margin-bottom:12px">1. We know roughly where and when language began, but not fully how or why</h3>' +
    '<ul style="color:#b0b0b0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.8;padding-left:20px">' +
      '<li>Language likely originated <strong style="color:#fff">100,000+ years ago</strong> in Africa</li>' +
      '<li>The <strong style="color:#fff">Austronesian dispersal</strong> from Taiwan (~3000 BC) shows how language families spread across the Pacific to Madagascar and Hawaii</li>' +
      '<li>We can trace language families and map their spread, but the exact origin of language itself — how and why it emerged — remains one of the biggest unsolved questions</li>' +
    '</ul>' +
  '</div>' +

  '<div style="margin-bottom:28px">' +
    '<h3 style="color:#fff;font-size:16px;margin-bottom:12px">2. Languages vary wildly in sounds, structure, and whether sound is even involved</h3>' +
    '<ul style="color:#b0b0b0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.8;padding-left:20px">' +
      '<li>Languages range from <strong style="color:#fff">11 phonemes</strong> (Rotokas) to <strong style="color:#fff">100+</strong> (Taa) — massive variation in the sounds used</li>' +
      '<li>Some languages are <strong style="color:#fff">analytic</strong> (English — separate words for each meaning), others are <strong style="color:#fff">polysynthetic</strong> (Cayuga — an entire sentence packed into one word: "I will plant potatoes for them again")</li>' +
      '<li>About <strong style="color:#fff">200 sign languages</strong> exist globally — full natural languages with their own grammar, not translations of spoken ones. Sound is not required for language.</li>' +
      '<li>Some languages lack word classes others consider basic — <strong style="color:#fff">Lao has no adjectives</strong></li>' +
      '<li>Languages even differ in basic concepts: some Aboriginal languages have <strong style="color:#fff">no word for "seven"</strong>, while Yeli Dnye has a single word meaning "20 days from today"</li>' +
    '</ul>' +
  '</div>' +

  '<div style="margin-bottom:28px">' +
    '<h3 style="color:#fff;font-size:16px;margin-bottom:12px">3. Linguistic diversity has waxed and waned throughout history</h3>' +
    '<ul style="color:#b0b0b0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.8;padding-left:20px">' +
      '<li><strong style="color:#fff">Peak: ~12,000 BC</strong> with roughly 100,000 languages — hunter-gatherer bands constantly splintered and spread, allowing languages to evolve independently</li>' +
      '<li><strong style="color:#fff">Today: ~7,000 languages</strong>, and declining fast. We are in a period of massive language extinction.</li>' +
      '<li>"Big" languages displace "little" ones — a process accelerated by <strong style="color:#fff">text-based technologies</strong> (writing, printing, internet) that let dominant languages scale</li>' +
      '<li>Striking correlation: regions with high <strong style="color:#fff">plant biodiversity</strong> (tropical rainforests) also have the highest concentration of distinct human languages</li>' +
      '<li>Just <strong style="color:#fff">23 languages</strong> are spoken by over half the world\'s population (4.1 billion people) — massive linguistic inequality</li>' +
      '<li>Papua New Guinea (about the size of California) has <strong style="color:#fff">~850 indigenous languages</strong> vs the US with ~150</li>' +
    '</ul>' +
  '</div>' +

  '<div style="margin-bottom:28px">' +
    '<h3 style="color:#fff;font-size:16px;margin-bottom:12px">4. The invention of writing was a "seismic event"</h3>' +
    '<ul style="color:#b0b0b0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.8;padding-left:20px">' +
      '<li>Writing invented <strong style="color:#fff">~3300 BC in Mesopotamia</strong> — originally for <strong style="color:#fff">accounting</strong> (3D clay tokens for tracking goods evolved into 2D marks on tablets), not for recording speech</li>' +
      '<li>Accelerated language extinction by giving big languages tools to scale and displace smaller ones</li>' +
      '<li>Changed human brains: a patch of the <strong style="color:#fff">visual cortex</strong> originally evolved for recognizing object contours in nature was "recycled" for reading — the <strong style="color:#fff">Visual Word Form Area</strong></li>' +
      '<li>Global literacy only <strong style="color:#fff">surpassed illiteracy after 1950</strong> — incredibly recent in human history</li>' +
      '<li>The <strong style="color:#fff">overbite</strong> (~3,600 years ago, from shift to softer agricultural diet) enabled <strong style="color:#fff">labiodental sounds</strong> like /f/ and /v/ by allowing top teeth to rest on the bottom lip</li>' +
    '</ul>' +
  '</div>' +

  '<div style="margin-bottom:16px">' +
    '<h3 style="color:#fff;font-size:16px;margin-bottom:12px">5. Face-to-face language is giving way to mediated forms</h3>' +
    '<ul style="color:#b0b0b0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.8;padding-left:20px">' +
      '<li>The <strong style="color:#fff">"primordial" form</strong> of language is in-person, face-to-face interaction</li>' +
      '<li>Writing, printing, the internet, and texting are all <strong style="color:#fff">mediated forms</strong> of language — communication without the other person being physically present</li>' +
      '<li>This shift from face-to-face to mediated communication is <strong style="color:#fff">extremely recent</strong> in the ~100,000-year history of human language, and its consequences are still unfolding</li>' +
      '<li>The <strong style="color:#fff">McGurk Effect</strong> shows how deeply tied language is to face-to-face context — visual information (seeing someone\'s mouth) actually changes what sounds we hear</li>' +
    '</ul>' +
  '</div>' +

  '</div>' +

  '<div class="card" style="margin-top:24px">' +
  '<h2 style="color:#fff;font-size:22px;margin-bottom:20px;font-weight:700">Lecture 2: Animal Communication Systems</h2>' +
  '<p style="color:#888;font-size:14px;margin-bottom:28px">Understanding human language by comparing it to how animals communicate — what makes us unique?</p>' +

  '<div style="margin-bottom:28px">' +
    '<h3 style="color:#fff;font-size:16px;margin-bottom:12px">1. We understand human language by comparing it to animal communication</h3>' +
    '<ul style="color:#b0b0b0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.8;padding-left:20px">' +
      '<li>To understand what makes human language special, researchers study animal communication systems "in the wild" — how animals naturally communicate without human training</li>' +
      '<li><strong style="color:#fff">Honeybees</strong> use the waggle dance to communicate the distance and direction of food sources — a sophisticated system, but rigid and limited to one topic</li>' +
      '<li><strong style="color:#fff">Vervet monkeys</strong> have specific alarm calls for different predators (eagle vs. snake vs. leopard) — showing basic referentiality (sounds that refer to specific things in the world)</li>' +
      '<li><strong style="color:#fff">Campbell\'s monkeys</strong> go further: they combine root calls with affixes (e.g., "hok" + "oo") to create new meanings — demonstrating basic compositionality (building complex meaning from smaller parts)</li>' +
    '</ul>' +
  '</div>' +

  '<div style="margin-bottom:28px">' +
    '<h3 style="color:#fff;font-size:16px;margin-bottom:12px">2. Key properties of human language are rare in animal systems</h3>' +
    '<ul style="color:#b0b0b0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.8;padding-left:20px">' +
      '<li><strong style="color:#fff">Referentiality</strong> — using a sound to refer to something in the world. Animals have basic referentiality (vervet alarm calls), but only humans have full referentiality for anything</li>' +
      '<li><strong style="color:#fff">Displaced referentiality</strong> — communicating about things not physically present. The honeybee\'s waggle dance does this (the food source is far away), making it a rare animal example</li>' +
      '<li><strong style="color:#fff">Compositionality</strong> — building complex meanings from smaller parts. Campbell\'s monkeys show a basic version, but human language does this at massive scale (infinite sentences from finite words)</li>' +
      '<li>These properties exist on a <strong style="color:#fff">continuum</strong> — it\'s not that animals have zero and humans have 100%, but humans are dramatically further along on every dimension</li>' +
    '</ul>' +
  '</div>' +

  '<div style="margin-bottom:28px">' +
    '<h3 style="color:#fff;font-size:16px;margin-bottom:12px">3. Human communication stands out in two key ways</h3>' +
    '<ul style="color:#b0b0b0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.8;padding-left:20px">' +
      '<li><strong style="color:#fff">Abstract referentiality</strong> — humans can refer to abstract concepts, invisible ideas, or things that don\'t physically exist (justice, love, the future, hypotheticals). No animal system does this.</li>' +
      '<li><strong style="color:#fff">Breadth of meaning</strong> — humans can talk about literally anything. Animal communication is typically limited to a narrow set of topics (food location, predator warnings, mating). Humans discuss philosophy, recipes, quantum physics, and gossip — all with the same system.</li>' +
      '<li>These two properties — abstractness and breadth — are what truly separate human language from everything else in the animal kingdom</li>' +
    '</ul>' +
  '</div>' +

  '<div style="margin-bottom:16px">' +
    '<h3 style="color:#fff;font-size:16px;margin-bottom:12px">4. Teaching animals human language has had limited success</h3>' +
    '<ul style="color:#b0b0b0;font-size:15px;line-height:1.8;padding-left:20px">' +
      '<li><strong style="color:#fff">Viki</strong> (chimpanzee) — raised as a human child in a human home. Could only physically produce 4 words. Proved apes lack the vocal tract anatomy for speech, leading researchers to try sign language instead.</li>' +
      '<li><strong style="color:#fff">Washoe</strong> (chimpanzee) — taught ASL manually. Learned signs but used them almost exclusively for <strong style="color:#fff">making requests</strong> (food, tickles, toys) — not sharing observations or discussing ideas.</li>' +
      '<li><strong style="color:#fff">Nim Chimpsky</strong> (chimpanzee) — another ASL study. Same pattern: mostly requests, no real sentence structure or grammar.</li>' +
      '<li><strong style="color:#fff">Kanzi</strong> (bonobo) — the most impressive case. Learned 200+ lexigrams <strong style="color:#fff">spontaneously without explicit instruction</strong> — just by observing. But still limited compared to human children.</li>' +
      '<li>The overall conclusion: apes can learn symbols and associate them with meanings, but their <strong style="color:#fff">communicative intention</strong> is almost entirely self-serving (requests). They don\'t use language the way humans do — to share knowledge, tell stories, or discuss abstract ideas.</li>' +
    '</ul>' +
  '</div>' +

  '<div style="text-align:center;padding:16px 0"><button class="btn btn-primary" onclick="toggleOverview()">Back to Quiz</button></div>' +
'</div>';
